activity.p:
Recall that eventually we would like an inner product to allow us to do geometry in vector spaces besides \R^n. As discussed in , the connection between the dot product and geometry in \R^n is
\unorm{v} \amp = \sqrt{\udotprod{v}{v}} \text{,} \amp \theta \amp = \inv{\cos} \left( \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}} \right) \text{.}
Based on this, what is the point of including Axiom RIP in our list of axioms?

introduction.p:
If we want to generalize in order to look for other, similar inner products, the first step is to look for an underlying pattern that can be changed. Notice that we can sneak an identity matrix in there: \udotprod{v}{w} = \utrans{\uvec{w}} I \uvec{v} . What if we change I to some other matrix A? Is
\uvecinprod{v}{w} = \utrans{\uvec{w}} A \uvec{v}
still an inner product?
